label.value: decreased homologous chromosome pairing at cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region on chromosome 3

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome pairing during meiosis (synapsis) is decreased (i.e. occurs to a lower extent) at a cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region on chromosome 3.

label.value: normal homologous chromosome pairing at cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region on chromosome 1

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome pairing during meiosis (synapsis) is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at a cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region on chromosome 1.

label.value: normal homologous chromosome pairing at cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region on chromosome 2

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome pairing during meiosis (synapsis) is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at a cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region on chromosome 2.

label.value: normal homologous chromosome pairing at cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region on chromosome 3

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome pairing during meiosis (synapsis) is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at a cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region on chromosome 3.
A cell phenotype in which the cell contains more Smp foci than normal.
A cellular process phenotype in which Smp focus formation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cell phenotype in which the cell does not contain a detectable Smp focus.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to heavy water (D2O). Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of heavy water that allows wild type cells to grow.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of heavy water (D2O) than normal.

label.value: decreased positive regulation of ATPase activity

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which positive regulation of an ATPase activity occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: abolished positive regulation of ATPase activity

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which positive regulation of an ATPase activity does not occur.

A molecular function phenotype in which DNA binding that bridges two double-stranded DNA regions does not occur, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of pyruvate kinase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of pyruvate kinase activity is increased.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of phosphoenolpyruvate measured in the cell is lower than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid measured in the cell is lower than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate measured in a cell is higher than normal.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell's energy charge higher than normal. Energy charge is a measure of energy available to the cell, as reflected in the ATP-ADP-AMP balance and defined as (ATP + 1/2 ADP)/(AMP + ADP + ATP).

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell's redox status differs from normal, as measured by the ratios of reduced to oxidized forms of one or more metabolites (e.g. NAD+:NADH).

label.value: increased cell population growth rate on fructose carbon source

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a cell population in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle grows at a faster rate than normal in a medium containing fructose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: increased cell population growth rate on sucrose carbon source

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a cell population in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle grows at a faster rate than normal in a medium containing sucrose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of chlorpromazine than normal.

label.value: abnormal histone methylation at silent mating-type cassette during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the methylation of histones in silent mating-type cassettes is abnormal. All histone methylation may be affected, or methylation of specific sites on specific histones may be altered.

label.value: abnormal histone methylation at centromere during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the methylation of histones in centromeric regions is abnormal. All histone methylation may be affected, or methylation of specific sites on specific histones may be altered.

label.value: abnormal histone methylation at telomere during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the methylation of histones in telomeric regions is abnormal. All histone methylation may be affected, or methylation of specific sites on specific histones may be altered.
A phenotype in which a region of the genome that is normally stably assembled and maintained as heterochromatin over successive generations entirely loses heterochromatic structure.

label.value: protein mislocalized to medial cortex during mitotic interphase

value.value: A  cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a protein that is not normally found at the medial cortex is observed there during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal spindle pole body-led chromosome movement during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which rapid, back-and-forth movement of the mitotic spindle pole body (SPB), and associated chromosome movement, is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). SPB oscillation occurs during mitotic interphase (as well as prophase) and is restricted to a small space.

A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a new growth zone forms along the lateral portion of the cell (often in the middle) before septation, such that a single cell grows in the form of the letter T.

definition.value: One distinction between T-shaped and other branched cells is that in T-shaped cells the new growth zone forms before NETO. A T-shaped cell may septate perpendicular to the normal septation axis, and divide to form normal-shaped daughter cells. Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'viable cell population' (FYPO:0002058) or one of its descendants.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is longer than normal, and a new growth zone forms along the lateral portion of the cell (often in the middle) before septation, such that a single cell grows in the form of the letter T.

definition.value: One distinction between T-shaped and other branched cells is that in T-shaped cells the new growth zone forms before NETO. A T-shaped cell may septate perpendicular to the normal septation axis, and divide to form normal-shaped daughter cells.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the protein Ssb1 accumulates in a large focus, or occasionally two foci, in the nucleus.

label.value: normal transcription regulatory region sequence-specific DNA binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of DNA binding at a transcription regulatory region by a gene product is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The relevant gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abolished protein localization to kinetochore during mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the kinetochore of a chromosome does not occur during mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein distribution along RNA polymerase II-transcribed genes during cellular response to oxidative stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the distribution of a protein localized to chromatin along the length of genes that can be transcribed by RNA polymerase II is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to oxidative stress.

definition.value: Usually assayed for RNA polymerase, transcription factors, or other components of the transcription machinery. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to another occurs for a longer time than normal. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.

label.value: decreased histone H2B-K119 ubiquitination during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which ubiquitination of lysine at position 119 of histone H2B occurs to a lower extent than normal. Lysine 119 corresponds to the conserved C-terminal lysine of H2B.

label.value: abolished NETO, with growth from new end

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the switch from the monopolar to bipolar mode of cell growth (new end take-off; NETO) does not occur, and the cell grows only from the new end.

A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the mitotic spindle is assembled in an incorrect orientation. Normally, the spindle is parallel to the long axis of the cell.

label.value: abnormal angle of spindle pole body-led chromosome movement during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which spindle pole body (SPB)-led chromosome movement in mitotic interphase takes place at an abnormal angle relative to the long axis of the cell. Normally, the SPB oscillation angle remains nearly parallel to the long axis.

label.value: increased variability of angle of spindle pole body-led chromosome movement during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which spindle pole body (SPB)-led chromosome movement in mitotic interphase takes place at an angle that varies more than normal. Normally, the SPB oscillation angle remains nearly parallel to the long axis of the cell.
A viability phenotype in which an aneuploid spore is unable to survive under conditions in which wild type spores survive. An inviable spore does not germinate.

definition.value: Thes phenotype can be observed after a polyploid meiosis, where aneuploid spores no longer form small colonies. This results in an increase of large to small colonies and decreased spore viability.

value.value: A cell phenotype in which that are aneuploid due to the presence of an extra copy of chromosome 3 lose the extra chromosome, producing haploid daughter cells, at a higher frequency than in otherwise wild-type cells.

definition.value: This phenotype results from increased chromosome instability in aneuploid cells, restores the cells to euhaploid, and causes haploid colonies to arise at a higher frequency.

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell has a septum with both ends at the cell tip(s). The normal location is at the midpoint of the long axis of the cell.

definition.value: Includes cells where both ends of the septum are found at the same end of the cell, and cells where one end of the septum is found at each end.

value.value: A phenotype in which the structure of one or more RNA molecules differs from normal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of heme into the cell is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of heme into the cell occurs to a lower extent than normal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of heme into the cell is abolished.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which signaling via a MAP kinase cascade that is activated in response to stress is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal protein localization to kinetochore during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the kinetochore of a chromosome is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to kinetochore during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the kinetochore of a chromosome does not occur during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
